Appendices

Appendix A: Mathematical Formalisms

A.1 Constrained Markov Decision Process (C-MDP) Formulation

The mission reasoning layer is formalized as a Constrained Markov Decision Process defined by the tuple \langle S, A, T, R, C, \gamma \rangle where:

· S: State space including rover position (x,y), orientation \theta, battery level b \in [0,100], thermal state t \in [-180,120]^{\circ}C, scientific targets discovered, and illumination status.
· A: Action space including drive commands (v, \omega), instrument deployment, communication beam steering, and hibernation mode.
· T(s'|s,a): Transition probability function capturing stochastic outcomes (slip, sensor noise, unexpected obstacles).
· R(s,a): Reward function combining scientific value and operational efficiency.
· C(s,a): Constraint function enforcing safety limits (battery > 20%, temperature within operational bounds).
· \gamma \in [0,1): Discount factor for future rewards.

Optimization Objective:

\max_{\pi} \mathbb{E}\left[\sum_{t=0}^{\infty} \gamma^t R(s_t, a_t) \right] \quad \text{subject to} \quad \mathbb{E}\left[\sum_{t=0}^{\infty} \gamma^t C(s_t, a_t) \right] \leq \epsilon

where \pi: S \rightarrow P(A) is the policy mapping states to action probabilities, and \epsilon represents the maximum acceptable cumulative constraint violation (e.g., total time spent below critical battery threshold).

A.2 POMDP Formulation for Perception Under Uncertainty

The perception layer implements a Partially Observable Markov Decision Process \langle S, A, O, T, Z, R, \gamma \rangle where:

· S: Hidden true state (actual terrain properties, rover pose).
· O: Observation space (camera images, LiDAR point clouds, wheel slip measurements).
· Z(o|s', a): Observation probability function modeling sensor noise characteristics.

The rover maintains a belief state b(s) = P(s | h) representing the probability distribution over hidden states given history h = (a_0, o_1, a_1, o_2, \ldots, a_{t-1}, o_t).

Belief Update (Recursive Bayesian Filtering):

b'(s') = \eta Z(o|s', a) \sum_{s \in S} T(s'|s,a) b(s)

where \eta is a normalization constant.

Value Function over Belief Space:

V(b) = \max_{a \in A} \left[ \sum_{s \in S} b(s) R(s,a) + \gamma \sum_{o \in O} P(o|b,a) V(b') \right]

A.3 Model Predictive Control for Energy-Aware Navigation

The navigation layer employs Model Predictive Control with receding horizon optimization:

\min_{u_{0:N-1}} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1} \left[ \underbrace{\alpha \| \mathbf{p}_k - \mathbf{p}_{\text{target}} \|^2}_{\text{goal attraction}} + \underbrace{\beta P_{\text{mobility}}(u_k, \theta_k, \mu_k)}_{\text{energy cost}} + \underbrace{\lambda \sigma^2_k}_{\text{uncertainty penalty}} \right]

subject to:

· Dynamics: \mathbf{p}_{k+1} = \mathbf{p}_k + f(\mathbf{p}_k, u_k, \mu_k) where \mu_k is slip coefficient
· Battery: b_{k+1} = b_k - (P_{\text{mobility}} + P_{\text{thermal}})\Delta t
· Illumination: I(\mathbf{p}_k, t_k) \geq I_{\text{min}} for sun-exposed traverses
· Control bounds: u_k \in \mathcal{U}

where u_k are control inputs (wheel torques, steering angles), \mathbf{p}_k is rover position, and \mu_k is predicted slip from Gaussian Process regression.

A.4 Control Barrier Functions for Safety Guarantees

Define a safe set \mathcal{S} = \{ x \in \mathbb{R}^n : h(x) \geq 0 \} where h(x) is a continuously differentiable function. A Control Barrier Function h(x) satisfies:

\sup_{u \in U} [L_f h(x) + L_g h(x)u] \geq -\alpha h(x)

for some extended class \mathcal{K} function \alpha. This condition ensures that if h(x(0)) \geq 0, then h(x(t)) \geq 0 for all t \geq 0 (forward invariance).

For the rover, we define multiple barrier functions:

· Battery safety: h_{\text{batt}}(x) = b - b_{\text{min}}
· Thermal safety: h_{\text{therm}}(x) = T_{\text{max}} - T and h_{\text{therm,min}}(x) = T - T_{\text{min}}
· Tip-over prevention: h_{\text{tip}}(x) = \theta_{\text{max}} - |\theta_{\text{roll}}|

The Survival Layer enforces:

\dot{h}_i(x) + \alpha_i h_i(x) \geq 0 \quad \forall i

by modulating or overriding high-level commands when necessary.

