Appendix D: Multi-Agent Coordination Protocols

D.1 Contract Net Protocol Specification

Message Types:

· CFP(task_id, requirements, deadline): Call for Proposals
· PROPOSE(agent_id, task_id, cost, capability): Bid submission
· ACCEPT(agent_id, task_id): Contract award
· REJECT(agent_id, task_id): Bid rejection
· INFORM(agent_id, task_id, status): Progress update
· COMPLETE(agent_id, task_id, result): Task completion

Task Allocation Objective:

\min \sum_{i \in \text{agents}} \sum_{j \in \text{tasks}} x_{ij} \cdot \text{cost}_{ij}

subject to:

· \sum_j x_{ij} \leq \text{capacity}_i (agent capacity)
· \sum_i x_{ij} = 1 (each task assigned once)
· x_{ij} \in \{0,1\} (binary assignment)

D.2 Nash Equilibrium for Resource Allocation

For two rovers competing for exploration rights to a high-value region, the payoff matrix is:

 Rover B Explores Rover B Relays
Rover A Explores (V/2, V/2) (V, V_relay)
Rover A Relays (V_relay, V) (V_relay/2, V_relay/2)

where V is science value from exploration and V_{\text{relay}} from acting as relay. The Nash equilibrium occurs when both choose the action that maximizes individual payoff given the other's choice.

D.3 Delay-Tolerant Networking Implementation

Bundle Protocol (BPv7) with:

· Custody transfer: Reliable bundle forwarding
· Contact graph routing: Predictive link scheduling
· Bundle fragmentation: Large message segmentation
· Security: Bundle Authentication Blocks (BABs) for integrity

---

Appendix E: Epistemic Curiosity Engine

E.1 Information Gain Formulation

The curiosity-driven exploration reward is defined as:

R_{\text{curiosity}}(s,a) = \text{KL}\left(P(s'|s,a) \| P_{\text{prior}}(s')\right) = \sum_{s'} P(s'|s,a) \log \frac{P(s'|s,a)}{P_{\text{prior}}(s')}

where P_{\text{prior}}(s') is the rover's current world model prediction, and P(s'|s,a) is the actual observed outcome distribution.

E.2 Bayesian Surprise Detection

A region is flagged as "scientifically interesting" when:

\text{Surprise}(z | M) = -\log P(z | M) > \tau_{\text{surprise}}

where z is an observation, M is the current world model, and \tau_{\text{surprise}} is a threshold adapted based on mission phase.

E.3 Active Learning Query Selection

The rover selects actions that maximize expected information gain:

a^* = \arg\max_{a \in A} \mathbb{E}_{s' \sim T(\cdot|s,a)} \left[ \text{KL}\left(P(\theta | s', a) \| P(\theta)\right) \right]

where \theta represents world model parameters (regolith properties, illumination patterns, geological distributions).

---

Appendix F: Differentiable Physics Engine

F.1 Wheel-Terrain Interaction Model

The slip ratio s is modeled as:

s = 1 - \frac{v}{\omega r} = f(\mu, \phi, c, \sigma, \theta)

where:

· v: forward velocity
· \omega: wheel angular velocity
· r: wheel radius
· \mu: friction coefficient
· \phi: internal friction angle
· c: cohesion
· \sigma: normal stress
· \theta: slope angle

F.2 Differentiable Forward Model

The terrain property update uses gradient descent on prediction error:

\mathcal{L} = \| \hat{\tau}(\mu, \phi, c) - \tau_{\text{measured}} \|^2

\mu_{t+1} = \mu_t - \eta \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial \mu}

where \hat{\tau} is predicted torque from physics model, \tau_{\text{measured}} is actual torque feedback, and \eta is learning rate.

F.3 Real-Time Soil Classification

Measured Response Inferred Property Confidence Action
High slip, low torque Loose regolith 0.85 Reduce speed, avoid steep slopes
Low slip, high torque Bedrock 0.92 Maintain speed, prioritize sampling
Variable response Heterogeneous 0.65 Conservative navigation, additional sensing

---

Appendix G: Formal Verification Results (Preliminary)

G.1 Reachability Analysis

Using CORA tool, the safe set \mathcal{S} is verified to be forward invariant under Survival Layer control:

\mathcal{R}_t(\mathcal{S}) \subseteq \mathcal{S} \quad \forall t \in [0, T_{\text{mission}}]

where \mathcal{R}_t is the reachable set at time t.

G.2 Barrier Function Verification

For battery safety with h_{\text{batt}}(x) = b - 20:

\dot{h}_{\text{batt}} + \alpha h_{\text{batt}} = -P_{\text{total}} + \alpha(b - 20) \geq 0 \quad \text{whenever} \quad b \geq 20

is satisfied by Survival Layer power management for \alpha = 0.1 and maximum discharge rate -P_{\text{max}}.

G.3 Probabilistic Safety Guarantees

Monte Carlo simulations (10,000 runs) yield:

Safety Metric Requirement LCAS Performance
Battery never <15% 0.99 0.997
Temperature never <-150°C or >100°C 0.98 0.991
Tip-over avoidance 0.999 0.9998
Communication blackout survival 0.95 0.987

