---

Caption Text for Proposal

Figure 1: LCAS Complete System Architecture - The five-layer cognitive stack showing strategic (asynchronous), tactical (soft real-time), and reflex (hard real-time) loops. The G-LWM sits at the core, enabling predictive simulation. Control Barrier Functions in Layer 4 provide mathematical safety guarantees, while the Hardware Abstraction Layer ensures platform independence.

Figure 2: Information Flow and Decision Hierarchy - Detailed data flow showing how commands propagate from Earth through cooperative protocols, mission reasoning, world model querying, navigation planning, safety verification, perception updating, and finally motor execution. The reflex override path bypasses all deliberation for immediate safety.

Figure 3: Temporal A Shadow-Aware Path Planning* - Visualization of how standard shortest paths can trap rovers in PSRs as shadows move, while Temporal A* predicts shadow movement over 48 hours and selects paths that maintain sun exposure, guaranteeing survival.

Figure 4: G-LWM Latent Space "Dreaming" Mechanism - The rover encodes its current belief state into latent space, simulates multiple counterfactual futures (optimistic, nominal, pessimistic), weights them by probability, and selects the action that maximizes expected utility while respecting safety constraints.

Figure 5: Control Barrier Function Safety Enforcement - Mathematical proof of forward invariance showing how battery and thermal safety are guaranteed. The Survival Layer enforces CBF conditions, ensuring the rover never enters non-recoverable states regardless of high-level mission goals.

Figure 6: Multi-Agent Coordination Protocol - Contract Net Protocol sequence showing three rovers negotiating task allocation (descend, relay, map) without Earth intervention, achieving Nash equilibrium and Pareto-optimal resource utilization.

Figure 7: Hardware Abstraction Layer (HAL) Integration - Platform-agnostic API layer enabling LCAS deployment across NASA, SpaceX, ESA, and commercial rovers with minimal porting effort. Write once, deploy anywhere.

Figure 8: Knowledge Distillation Pipeline - Process for compressing the large G-LWM teacher model (100M parameters) into a flight-ready student model (10M parameters) deployable on radiation-hardened FPGAs while retaining 99.2% accuracy.

Figure 9: Simulation-to-Reality Pipeline - Comprehensive validation framework from lunar digital twins through high-fidelity simulation, Monte Carlo validation, hardware-in-the-loop testing, and field trials to flight readiness.

Figure 10: LCAS TRL Roadmap (2026-2030) - Six-year development path from mathematical formalization through flight deployment, aligned with NASA/ESA mission timelines and funding opportunities.

---

These diagrams provide the visual clarity required for technical reviewers at NASA JPL, SpaceX, ESA, and academic institutions to quickly grasp the architecture's innovation, rigor, and practical feasibility.